# Compodoc Setup for Storybook Angular

## Installation

First, install the Compodoc dependency:

```bash
npm install --save-dev @compodoc/compodoc
```

## Enable Compodoc in angular.json

Update your Angular project's builder configuration in `angular.json` to activate Compodoc:

```json
{
  "projects": {
    "your-project": {
      "architect": {
        "storybook": {
          "builder": "@storybook/angular:start-storybook",
          "options": {
            "compodoc": true,
            "compodocArgs": [
              "-e",
              "json",
              "-d",
              "."
            ]
          }
        },
        "build-storybook": {
          "builder": "@storybook/angular:build-storybook",
          "options": {
            "compodoc": true,
            "compodocArgs": [
              "-e",
              "json",
              "-d",
              "."
            ]
          }
        }
      }
    }
  }
}
```

## Configure setCompodocJson in preview.ts

Add the following to your `.storybook/preview.ts` file:

```typescript
import type { Preview } from '@storybook/angular';
import { setCompodocJson } from '@storybook/addon-docs/angular';
import docJson from '../documentation.json';

setCompodocJson(docJson);

const preview: Preview = {
  // ...
};

export default preview;
```

## Adding JSDoc Comments

"You can include JSDoc comments above components, directives, and other parts of your Angular code to include documentation for those elements." Focus on documenting `@Inputs` and `@Outputs`, as these are the primary interactive elements exposed in Storybook controls.

